# Architecture Plan

Product/repo: alex-0d18-test-22. No PRODUCT.md is present in the workspace, so this plan is based on the existing GitHub issue text and README.

## Project Shape

- Use a Vite React SPA with TypeScript.
- Keep the app static-build friendly, with `npm run build` producing deployable files under `dist/`.
- Organize source under `src/`:
  - `src/App.tsx`: application container that owns calculator state and wires UI events to the engine.
  - `src/main.tsx`: React entry point.
  - `src/styles.css`: Tailwind base/imports and global app styles.
  - `src/engine/calculator.ts`: pure calculator reducer/actions and arithmetic behavior.
  - `src/engine/types.ts`: shared state, operation, action, and display status types.
  - `src/engine/format.ts`: display formatting, precision trimming, and overflow-safe string helpers.
  - `src/components/Display.tsx`: presentational display for current input/result/error.
  - `src/components/Keypad.tsx`: responsive keypad emitting typed calculator actions.
  - `src/test/` or colocated `*.test.ts`: unit tests for engine and formatting.
  - `e2e/`: browser tests for full calculation flows after UI wiring.

## Shared Types and State Model

- `Operation`: `"add" | "subtract" | "multiply" | "divide"`.
- `CalculatorState`:
  - `currentInput: string`: editable operand text, preserving decimal-entry intent.
  - `accumulator: number | null`: committed left-hand value for chained evaluation.
  - `pendingOperation: Operation | null`: operation waiting for the next operand.
  - `overwriteInput: boolean`: next digit replaces result/current input after operation/evaluation.
  - `error: string | null`: displayable error state, primarily division by zero.
- `CalculatorAction`: typed actions for digit, decimal, operation, equals, sign toggle, percentage, clear entry, clear all, and keyboard-derived input.
- Engine functions must be pure and deterministic so unit tests can cover behavior independently of React.

## Issue Dependencies

- Issue #1 creates the Vite React TypeScript baseline and static build scripts.
- Issue #2 adds Tailwind, ESLint, Prettier, and base styling on top of #1.
- Issue #3 introduces the engine state model and entry actions after project structure exists.
- Issue #4 builds arithmetic/evaluation on top of #3.
- Issue #5 adds percentage and C/AC behavior once entry and arithmetic state are stable.
- Issue #6 tests the completed engine behaviors from #3 through #5.
- Issue #7 builds `Display` after styling is available.
- Issue #8 builds `Keypad` after the React structure exists.
- Issue #9 connects `App` to engine plus display/keypad and adds keyboard input.
- Issue #10 adds end-to-end coverage after the UI is wired.
- Issue #11 reviews error handling and verifies/document static production build.

## Key Design Decisions

- Keep calculation logic out of React components. Components receive display data and emit typed actions.
- Store current input as a string to avoid losing user intent during decimal entry, sign toggling, and trailing-zero input.
- Evaluate chained operations left-to-right, matching the issue scope instead of implementing operator precedence.
- Represent division by zero as an engine error state that the display can render without throwing.
- Make `C` clear only the current entry when there is active input or pending state, and `AC` reset the full calculator state.
- Use formatting only at the display boundary; keep engine numeric state unformatted.
- Use Vitest and React Testing Library for unit/component tests, and Playwright for the full browser calculation flow.
